05637nam a22007695i 9780823292615DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232926157 a10.1515/97808232926152doi  a(DE-B1597)565962  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aMUS0200002bisacsh00aSpeaking of Music :bAddressing the Sonorous /ced. by Andrew H. Clark, Keith Chapin. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b11 Illustrations, black and white  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tSpeaking of Music: A View across Disciplines and a Lexicon of Topoi -- tSpeaking of Music -- tWaiting for the Death Knell: Speaking of Music (So to Speak) -- tBach’s Silence, Matthe son’s Words: Professional and Humanist Ways of Speaking of Music -- tMaking Music Speak -- tRousseau: Music, Language, and Politics -- tListening to Music -- tMi manca la voce: How Balzac Talks Music—or How Music Takes Place—in Massimilla Doni -- tSpeaking of Music in the Romantic Era: Dynamic and Resistant Aspects of Musical Genre -- tWeather Reports: Discourse and Musical Cognition -- tMessiaen, Deleuze, and the Birds of Proclamation -- tParole, parole: Tautegory and the Musicology of the (Pop) Song -- tSpeaking of Microsound: The Bodies of Henri Chopin -- tOn the Ethics of the Unspeakable -- tRécit Recitation Recitative -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPeople chat about music every day, but they also treat it as a limit, as the boundary of what is sayable. By addressing different perspectives and traditions that form and inform the speaking of music in Western culture—musical, literary, philosophical, semiotic, political—this volume offers a unique snapshot of today’s scholarship on speech about music. The range of considerations and material is wide. Among others, they include the words used to interpret musical works (such as those of Beethoven), the words used to channel musical practices (whether Bach’s, Rousseau’s, or Hispanic political protesters’), and the words used to represent music (whether in a dialogue by Plato, in a story by Balzac, or in an Italian popular song). The contributors consider the ways that music may slide by words, as in the performance of an Akpafu dirge or in Messiaen, and the ways that music may serve as an embodied figure, as in the writings of Diderot or in the sound and body art of Henri Chopin. The book concludes with an essay by Jean-Luc Nancy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBrandt, Per Aage, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapin, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapin, Keith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClark, Andrew H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Andrew H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGelbart, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, John T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKramer, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaas, Sander van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreno, Jairo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNancy, Jean-Luc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOdello, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrong, Tracy B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.